Spray imedachlorprid 17.8 SL (Admire, confidor 200 SC, 250 ml per hectare) 5-7 ml at 15 liter of water.

Spray Lambda Cyhalothrin 5% EC 120 to 150 ml at per acre or 12-15 ml per pump.
Triazofos 40 EC 20-25 ml per pump 
profenophos 40 % 20-25 ml per pump
Azadirachtin 0.03% Min. Neem Oil Based E.C. Containing 40-45 ml per pump
Fenthion 100 EC 1 ml per liter or 15-17 ml per pump 
Spray Carbaryl (4 g/litre of water) or Metacid (1ml/litre of water) during the seedling stage effectively controls the pest.

Spray Thiacloprid 21.7 % SC @ 6.0 ml/10 lit. 
Spray Oxydemeton –Methyl 25 % EC @ 1.0 ml/lit. 
Spray Dichlorvos 76% EC @ 250-350 ml/acre. 
Spray daiphenthuran 50 % WP (pegasas) 10 to 15 gram at per pump.
Spray of Acephate 75% SP @ 300-400 gm/acre

Recommended  for The crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root intiation : 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage : 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage : 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage : 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

KCCAns: The requirement of irrigation on the basis of onion crop depends on the variety of soil, state of crop and season. Immediately after the transplanting of the plants, light irrigation must be done and after 2-3 days then light irrigation, so that the soil remains moist and the plants get well frozen. 10-12 irrigation is enough on the onion crop. There should be no shortage of water while forming the bulb. Due to excessive irrigation, it is possible to get purple smear disease, whereas there may be problem of bursting in the condition of drying in the field for more time. Irrigation should be stopped 15 days before digging. Irrigation by drip method increases the yield of 40-50% with the increase of 15-20% in yield.

Also 0.6 to 1.6 m for the line of litter. Is left in place. Planting up to 400-800 plants in a kheri For this, kiri is excavated. It is about 0.3 m Dug up and root, peg and pebbles are extracted. The dump on the ground is mixed well. This soil is left open for one month and after that it is filled with sand and organic compost in kiri. To prevent water logging in moisture area, the level of the floor is raised to 30 cm high. In dry areas, kari is kept at the level of the ground. Especially in extremely dry areas where there is 750 mm of rain, the dip in the water gives good results. From a standard Kri, which is 12 m It is about 3 to 12 kg of seeds used.

1- Visit the field in which sampling is to be done by jig-jig and mark it at 10-15 places so that all parts of the farm can be included in it.

2- Remove debris, debris etc. from the upper surface on the selected places.

3- 15 cm at all these places (6-9 inch) dig deeper V shaped cord. Cleansing the pot from the top of the scalp, up to 2 cm from the top. Remove the thick soil from the bottom and put it in a clean bucket or tray.

4- Mix the collected clay well with hand and make a round pile by putting it on clean clothes. Remove the clay from finger to four equal parts and remove the soil separately. Now mix the remaining two parts again and make the rounds. Repeat this procedure until almost half of the remains are left in the soil. This representative will be sample.

5- Keep the dry soil sample in a clean plastic bag and put it in a garment bag. Insert a notice sheet with a sample on which all the information is written, inside a plastic bag and outside a garment bag.
